New Student Enrollment for 2020-21 is NOW available online at wyomingps.org! To enroll, click "Online Enrollment - New Students for 2020-21 School Year". If your child is NEW to Wyoming Public Schools for the 2020-21 school year, please use this online enrollment process.
If you cannot enroll online, you can pick up a paper enrollment packet at our Administration Office (3575 Gladiola Ave SW). There is a box outside the main door with paper enrollment packets and a secure drop box to return them when they are complete.
If you have any questions, email pvue@wyomingps.org or call 616-530-7550. ğŸ’œğŸº

text:
#BetterTogetherWPS ğŸ’œğŸº

Zach Harig - Fox 17
March 16 at 5:57 PM Â·

Wyoming Public Schools has set up two food distribution sites to help students & families in need.

"I don't know what we would have done without the extra help," mother Amber Harper said, "we're on state assistance and with my kids home every day, it becomes the same struggle as the summer time."

post_text: Thankful for our community partners! #BetterTogetherWPS #WyomingWolves
shared_text:
School News Network
March 5 at 11:16 AM Â·

Wyoming Public Schools educators and volunteers recently joined forces with business leaders to keep students warm.

The One Wyoming Community Drive for winter clothing Jan. 20 to Feb. 21 resulted in boxes full of coats, mittens, hats and snow pants for students at Parkview Elementary School, Oriole Park Elementary, Gladiola Elementary and West Elementary School. They will be distributed to students as needed.

Staff members, volunteers and Kent School Services Network partnered with several local businesses, to collect donated items.

Gladiola Principal Cheryl Corpus said many elementary students district-wide were going without winter clothing and this was a way to outfit them with what they need. â€œIf you are a student in need we will support you,â€ she said.

School News Network
March 5 at 11:16 AM Â·

Wyoming Public Schools educators and volunteers recently joined forces with business leaders to keep students warm.

The One Wyoming Community Drive for winter clothing Jan. 20 to Feb. 21 resulted in boxes full of coats, mittens, hats and snow pants for students at Parkview Elementary School, Oriole Park Elementary, Gladiola Elementary and West Elementary School. They will be distributed to students as needed.

Staff members, volunteers and Kent School Services Network partnered with several local businesses, to collect donated items.

Gladiola Principal Cheryl Corpus said many elementary students district-wide were going without winter clothing and this was a way to outfit them with what they need. â€œIf you are a student in need we will support you,â€ she said.

Every 10 years, the U.S. Census Bureau undertakes a mammoth task: counting all the people residing in the United States. This count affects the allocation of funding for our community's public resources (e.g., schools, roads, hospitals), how we plan for the future, and our voice in government. Learn more about the importance of the #2020Census and how to participate:
www.2020census.gov
